		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Richmond</placeName> <date>Sept 4&#44; 1852</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend&#33;</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">By the favourable oppor&#45;<lb/>tunity afforded by our friend <persName>Mr Mailert</persName><lb/> leaving for your place&#44; I drop you<lb/> a few lines hoping that they may<lb/> meet you in the enjoyment of that<lb/> vigo<del>u</del>rous state of mind which the al&#45;<lb/>mighty has for years past endowed<lb/> you with. My health during<lb/> this summer has been much enfeebled<lb/> but thank God I am much impro&#45;<lb/>ved.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I read your last no of the<lb/> &#8220;Occident&#8221; with much delight&#44; your<lb/> views as to the wants of our people<lb/> could not have been better portrayed&#44;<lb/> the question is&#44; how can it be spee&#45;<lb/>dily accomplished&#44; year after year<lb/> has glided away since your noble<lb/> scheme of a convention has been pro&#45;<lb/>posed. If that cannot be effected&#44; we<lb/> can do nothing&#44; as that scheme has laid<lb/> <sic>dorment</sic> so long&#44; and as the New Yorkers<lb/> are so jealous on any subject that does<lb/> not originate with them&#44; could we not</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>get them to make a new move in the matter&#44;<lb/> let them have the honor and the glory of<lb/> reviving the subject&#44; something must be<lb/> done.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">&#8220;Our Ritual and its Recital&#8221; has claimed<lb/> much notice here as also <persName>Mr Eckman&#39;s</persName> ar&#45;<lb/>ticle&#44; they contain stubborn facts and they<lb/> must be remedied&#44; I often wished that<lb/> some reformation could be made in the<lb/> recital of our ritual&#44; my principal&#44; and<lb/> instructions that I have invariably given<lb/> to our hazanim here has been&#44; &#8220;that<lb/> every portion of the device that is read<lb/> in the synagogue should be read in<lb/> a slow&#44; distinct and impressive manner<lb/> irregardless of the time that it occupies&#44;&#8221;<lb/> if the Form of Service is too long for to be<lb/> recited in that manner in reasona&#45;<lb/>ble length of time&#44; steps should be taken<lb/> to have them curtailed by omitting all<lb/> <sic>repititions</sic>&#44; The Catholics have their<lb/> &#8220;Three hail Mary&#39;s &#38;c&#8221; it is not necessary<lb/> for us to have these repetitions.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Only look at the Kipur service where<lb/> &#8220;<add>&#63;</add>&#8221; are repeated so often. &#8220;El Meleck<lb/> yosheb&#8221; is rattled away ridiculous and<lb/> so it goes through the whole of the ser&#45;<lb/>vice the Question arises&#44; how are our<lb/> children to learn to say their prayers</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>with that devotion necessary for the recital of<lb/> our sublime ritual&#44; it gives the high min&#45;<lb/>ded adult a distaste for the service&#44; now<lb/> contrast our service with that of the gentiles<lb/> only see how decorous every part of their<lb/> service is performed. When you enter into<lb/> some of their churches we are struck with<lb/> awe we are reminded often with the solemn<lb/> scriptural injunction of &#8220;the Lord is in this<lb/> holy Temple let all the earth keep si&#45;<lb/>lence before Him.&#8221;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">There must be something done to stimu&#45;<lb/>late this lukewarmness existing amongst<lb/> our Co&#45;religionists&#44; had I but the power<lb/> to <sic>weild</sic> the pen and give vent my fee<lb/>lings in this matter.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I am aware that any attempt to ab&#45;<lb/>ridge our form of service would meet<lb/> with opposition at first&#44; but as it is<lb/> not the old mosaic or Temple form of<lb/> service I see no good reason why the<lb/> change cannot be made to suit the<lb/> country &#38; times in which we live. I wish we<lb/> had but one minhag in <placeName>America</placeName>&#44; and the<lb/> service read in good grammatical Hebrew&#44;<lb/> any thing that I in my feeble efforts can<lb/> effect&#44; God knows I am willing to<lb/> do&#44; hoping to hear soon. I remain yours &#38;c</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Jacob Ezekiel</persName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(3)"><placeName>Pa</placeName></p>
			<p>Favd by</p>
			<p><persName>Mr A. Mailert</persName></p>
          
